SIMPLE: retreat
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Retreat
<hw>Re*treat"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>retraite</ets>, fr. <ets>retraire</ets> to withdraw, L.
<ets>retrahere</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>trahere</ets> to
draw. See <er>Trace</er>, and cf. <er>Retract</er>,
<er>Retrace</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of retiring or
withdrawing one's self, especially from what is dangerous or
disagreeable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In a <qex>retreat</qex> he outruns any lackey.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The place to which anyone retires; a place or
privacy or safety; a refuge; an asylum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He built his son a house of pleasure, and spared no cost to make a
delicious <qex>retreat</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That pleasing shade they sought, a soft <qex>retreat</qex>⟦br⟧
From sudden April showers, a shelter from the heat.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil. & Naval.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The retiring
of an army or body of men from the face of an enemy, or from any ground
occupied to a greater distance from the enemy, or from an advanced
position.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The withdrawing of a ship or fleet
from an enemy for the purpose of avoiding an engagement or escaping
after defeat.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A signal given in the army or
navy, by the beat of a drum or the sounding of trumpet or bugle, at
sunset (when the roll is called), or for retiring from action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ A <xex>retreat</xex> is properly an orderly march, in
which circumstance it differs from a <xex>flight</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A special season of
solitude and silence to engage in religious exercises.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A period of several days of withdrawal from society to
a religious house for exclusive occupation in the duties of devotion;
<as>as, to appoint or observe a <ex>retreat</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Retirement; departure; withdrawment; seclusion;
solitude; privacy; asylum; shelter; refuge.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retreat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Retreat
<hw>Re*treat"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Retreated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Retreating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make a retreat; to retire
from any position or place; to withdraw; <as>as, the defeated army
<ex>retreated</ex> from the field</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rapid currents drive⟦br⟧
Towards the <qex>retreating</qex> sea their furious tide.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retreatful</ent>⟦br⟧
